# Benchmarking SLAM Algorithms for Indoor AGV Navigation Using ROS2 and Gazebo

## Overview
Reliable localization and mapping are critical for autonomous mobile robots operating in indoor environments. This project investigates the performance of several Simultaneous Localization and Mapping (SLAM) algorithms through a simulation-based benchmarking study.

Using ROS2 and Gazebo with a TurtleBot3 simulation platform, multiple SLAM algorithms were implemented and evaluated under consistent navigation parameters across controlled indoor environments.

The objective is to identify the most suitable SLAM configuration for accurate and reliable indoor AGV navigation.

---

## Objectives
- Implement multiple SLAM algorithms within a ROS2 navigation framework
- Evaluate the performance of each SLAM method under identical simulation conditions
- Compare localization accuracy and mapping quality
- Identify the most suitable algorithm for indoor autonomous navigation

---

## System Architecture
The simulation environment consists of:

Robot Platform:
- TurtleBot3

Simulation Environment:
- Gazebo

Middleware:
- ROS2

Navigation Stack:
- ROS2 Navigation2

SLAM Algorithms Tested:
- GMapping
- Cartographer
- SLAM Toolbox

Each SLAM algorithm was integrated into the same navigation framework to ensure fair comparison across experiments.

---

## Experimental Methodology
The benchmarking process was conducted in multiple simulated indoor environments.

Each SLAM algorithm was tested using identical robot motion parameters and sensor configurations.

Performance metrics were collected for each experiment to evaluate localization accuracy and mapping quality.

---

## Evaluation Metrics
The following metrics were used for comparison:

Trajectory RMSE  
Measures the deviation between the estimated trajectory and the ground truth trajectory.

Map Quality  
Evaluates the accuracy and consistency of the generated occupancy grid map.

Navigation Completion Time  
Measures the time required for the robot to complete predefined navigation tasks.

---

## Results
A comparative analysis was performed across the tested SLAM algorithms to determine their performance in indoor navigation scenarios.

The evaluation results highlight differences in localization accuracy, mapping consistency, and computational efficiency.

The best-performing SLAM configuration from this study will be used in subsequent work focusing on real-world localization error analysis and system improvement.

---

## Key Skills Demonstrated
- Robot Operating System (ROS2)
- Gazebo robotic simulation
- SLAM algorithm implementation
- autonomous navigation systems
- robotics system benchmarking
- performance evaluation using RMSE metrics
